Diseases like AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENÈVE - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable proof that the use of tobacco, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of premature death from non-communicable diseases.
Yet, despite extensive knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that non-communicable disease alliances networks got together from 9 to 11 December at the second Global Alliance on Non-Communicable Diseases Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating MNT, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress achieved.
As the battle is not over, HIV/AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against MNT can push back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet magazine, described the MNT community as being in wait for an "electroshock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it to them ?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
While the world's attention is focused on preventing STIs, those who seek to manage avoidable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS organizations.
The first letter that the STI community must take into account is "A", as activism.
Anyone over 40 years old certainly remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even closed the Food and Drug Administration headquarters for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have pressed governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medications more affordable.
This activism is continuing and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the NCD Community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the 'B' of the movement's strategy against HIV/AIDS.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can federate the first energies, but organizing and maintaining a large coalition requires money.
The HIV/AIDS movement has been clear on this point from the start and has pressed for resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
« C » represents coalitions: movements fighting AIDS did not take long to understand that progress comes only with several supporters.
Activists established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders to public authorities in order to combine their views and expertise.
The AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, 'D', the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectivity of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about the timing and person with whom to negotiate protected sex.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a major role in the AIDS crisis.
MDTs (Multidisciplinary Teams) are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Commitment - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategic borrowings from the disability rights movement, which defended the key phrase "Nothing about us without us", advocates for the AIDS cause demanded representation of existing organizations to treat the disease.
For example, the UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Board of Directors for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so strongly integrated into the HIV/AIDS fight movement that it would be almost unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
The disease prevention movements must also develop convincing stories and 'F' - the question formulation - is essential so that the HIV/AIDS community can obtain support from political leaders.
In particular, access to HIV/AIDS treatments has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the story in this way leads to a significant reduction in the price of medications, to the point that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are under treatment.
The formulation of the question that is equally important for AIDS, a very relevant question for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to put more emphasis on the life choices of individuals, rather than attributing the responsibility of the state in the provision of healthcare and in the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, the gender - the "G" of our movement - was a significant point.
Initially, HIV was considered a "gay disease" and gender identity was anchored from the beginning in the DNA of the AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: suffice it to examine how alcohol and tobacco are commercialized to understand this.
The genre, therefore, must become a center of efforts for the prevention of NTDs.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in workplaces, schools, and medical centers.
The strategic lawsuit has ensured equality under the law.
The HIV/AIDS movement has refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactics, for instance, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue along the alphabet with the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but it seems appropriate to close with "H" given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at a higher risk of contracting HIV.
The same goes for MNT.
The initial reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS fight movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The MNT and HIV/AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
